<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> DVD Player... who doesn't have a DVD player already? And really, is the $100 worth a generic, optionless DVD player. Take the $100 you saved with GC, save up another $100, and buy a decent DVD player... /nod<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't have the money to fork over an extra $100 for a DVD player, however the PS2 offered a very nice way for me to get a DVD player.<br>
<br>
Frankly though Nintendo needs to step up to the plate if they wanna play in the game. The 64 was a failure, even with a few wildly popular games, it still flopped. It was a good system, but it didn't have the games behind it to back it up.<br>
<br>
Nintendo as a company cannot survive forever on adventure games. They just can't do it, that's what the 64 was. It had no speakable RPGs, although the SNES did have some very nice RPGs 2 of which are in my top 2 of all time.<br>
<br>
Stepping back and looking at it from a pretty objective view, I owned NES and SNES, I own a PS1 and PS2, I own a computer using a Windows98(a Microsoft product of course), I'm pretty objective I own something from each company, none of which I have any real complaints with. I've also played X-box and GameCube, and played a lot on the N64.<br>
<br>
Sony - Damn these guys just know how to do it.<br>
Nintendo - Great company that makes good stuff, but needs to step up and put forth a better effort.<br>
Microsoft - Made a damn nice system that has suprised a lot of people, however they've gotta crank out the games in order to compete.<br>
Sega - Damn I wish these guys knew how to market, the DreamCast is a nice system with some great games, but they can't market worth a fly fuck. The one guy keeping the company going died a while back, I just hope they do better as a developer then they did as a producer.<br>
<br>
<br>
